{{Orphan|date=September 2016}}
'''Cracked After Hours''' was a comedy [[web series]] hosted on the website [[Cracked.com]], and produced by Cracked and its parent company [[The E. W. Scripps Company]].<ref>[http://www.digiday.com/video/demand-medias-unlikely-success-story/ "Demand Media's Unlikely Success Story"]. ''[[Digiday]]''.</ref><ref>[http://www.comedyspotnation.com/web-series-after-hours-at-cracked-com/ "Web Series: ‘After Hours’ at Cracked.com."]. ''Comedy Spot Nation'' On April 18, 2013 In Featured Reviews</ref>
{{TOC right}}
== Overview == The scripted comedy follows four friends/co-workers of Cracked.com who meet after work at their local diner.<ref name=dead>[http://comedytvisdead.com/2013/03/10/cracked-after-hours-or-how-to-do-internet-comedy-right/ "Cracked After Hours; Or, How to do Internet Comedy Right "]. ''Comedy TV is Dead''. 2013-03-10.</ref><ref>[http://www.bleedingcool.com/2014/11/08/comikaze-panel/ "Behind The Scenes Of A Future Cracked: After Hours Episode"]. ''Bleeding Cool'', . November 8, 2014. Michele Brittany.</ref> The Seinfeldian conversations usually result in heavily disputed opinions about pop culture and life in general.<ref>[http://www.tubefilter.com/2012/03/26/cracked-after-hours/ "Geeks Argue About Mario After Hours"]. ''TubeFilter'', By Chris Landa. March 26, 2012.</ref><ref>[https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2014/12/the-10-best-web-series-of-2014.html "The 10 Best Web Series of 2014"]. By Shannon M. Houston | December 31, 2014</ref>
The series was launched on July 19, 2010 with an episode centered around the 1985 film ''[[Back to the Future]]'', and grew to become the most viewed web series on Cracked.com.<ref name=dead /> The show's first 13 episodes reached 15 million views by April 2012 <ref>[https://www.forbes.com/sites/ryanholiday/2012/04/16/exclusive-how-comedian-daniel-obrien-turned-one-joke-into-a-major-book-deal/ "How Comedian Daniel O'Brien Turned One Joke Into a Major Book Deal"]. ''Forbes'', 2012-04-16.</ref> and it has since expanded to 30 episodes and surpassed 25 million total views.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}} It stars Cracked.com employees Michael Swaim, [[Daniel O'Brien (comedian)|Daniel O'Brien]],<ref>[http://www.geekscape.net/geekscape-interviews-agents-of-cracked-star-dan-obrien "Geekscape Interviews Agents of Cracked Star Dan O'Brien"]. ''Geekscape'', Jun 28, 2011.</ref> and Soren Bowie<ref>[http://fanboynation.com/we-get-crackin-up-with-cracked-com/ "We get Crackin’ Up with Cracked.com"]. ''FanBoy Nation'', November 11, 2014. Christie Shinn</ref> and regular Cracked contributor Katie Willert.<ref>[http://www.paste.com/issues/week-18/articles/after-hours-answering-lifes-least-important-questions "After Hours- Answering Life's Least Important Questions"]. ''Paste Magazine]''</ref> Most episodes are written by one of the stars or series co-creator Jack O'Brien, with help from the Cracked team.<ref>[http://www.statedmag.com/articles/profile-after-hours-works-the-late-shift-on-crackedcom.html# "After Hours Works the Late Shift"]. ''Stated Magazine'',</ref>
The series integrates crudely [[Animation|animated]] segments created by artists Winston Roundtree, Brett Herholz, Anthony Clark, and Matt Barrs. Characters' thoughts are illustrated by thought-bubbles or full-screen display. The first 22 episodes were directed by Justin Viar. Subsequent episodes have been directed by Abe Epperson and Adam Ganser.
In 2013 ''After Hours'' was nominated for a Webby Award.<ref>[http://www.thevideoink.com/breaking-news/nominees-18th-annual-webby-awards/#.VB9KFRYQZco "And the Nominees for the 18th Annual Webby Awards Are…"]. ''The Video Ink''.</ref><ref>[http://www.webbyawards.com/winners/2014/online-film-video/performance-craft/best-writing/ "2014:Best Writing"]. ''Webby Awards''</ref>
===Introduction of Second Cast (2017)=== The July 24, 2017 episode "Awkward Scenes That Must Have Happened In Marvel Movies" introduced a second cast of diner patrons: Yazmin Monet Watkins, Kimia Behpoornia, Cracked writer Carmen Angelica and Cracked head writer for video Cody Johnston.<ref>''[http://www.cracked.com/blog/awkward-Scenes-That-Must-Have-Happened-In-Marvel-Movies/ Awkward Scenes That Must Have Happened In Marvel Movies]''. ''Cracked'', July 24, 2017. Daniel O'Brien</ref> This group meets at the same diner, and has similar pop culture conversations. Before its cancelation, episodes of this second cast were to be released monthly, alongside new episodes from the original cast.
===Possible cancellation=== Prior to December 4, 2017, Soren Bowie had left Cracked to pursue another writing job while Michael Swaim<ref>[ https://twitter.com/SWAIM_CORP/status/938185966954541056 "Michael Swaim's Official Twitter"]. ''Twitter.com''.</ref> had quit in October to pursue other media. On December 4, 2017, Cracked laid off a significant number of staff members, including Daniel O'Brien<ref>[https://twitter.com/DOB_INC/status/937870512679665665 "Daniel O'Brien's Official Twitter"]. ''Twitter.com''.</ref>, Carmen Angelica<ref>[ https://twitter.com/Carmesancheeses/status/938091460301275136 "Carmen Angelica's Official Twitter"]. ''Twitter.com''.</ref>, and Cody Johnston<ref>[ https://twitter.com/drmistercody/status/937927201172754432 "Cody Johnston's Official Twitter"]. ''Twitter.com''.</ref>. No official statement has been made regarding Yazmin Watkins or Kimia Behpoornia's continued involvement.
